One more thought

I don’t think the mascot should be the hero.

The customer is.

The Hawg is almost like a guide or a reminder.

Think of him as the version of yourself that stayed wild.

Not a superhero.

Not a cartoon.

A symbol.

When someone reaches into the bag at 6:00 AM before work, the bag isn’t saying:

Look at this cool boar.

It’s quietly saying:

Remember who you are.

That’s a surprisingly timeless message.

And I think it’s bigger than energy gummies.

One last idea I’d write in the notebook is this:

Wild Hawg doesn’t sell energy. Wild Hawg sells agency.

Energy is the mechanism.

Agency—the feeling that you can go do the thing you were putting off—is what people are really hoping to buy. If your product consistently supports that feeling, you’ll have something that’s much harder for competitors to copy than a flavor or an ingredient list.